Sentencas: A numerical methodology for evaluating the three-phase boundary length (TPBL) in sintered composite solid oxide fuel cell electrodes is developed.
Titulo: Connected Three-Phase Boundary Length Evaluation in Modeled Sintered Composite Solid Oxide Fuel Cell Electrodes

Sentencas: Three-dimensional models of a representative volume element of sintered composite electrodes are generated for which the mean particle diameter, composition, and total porosity may be specified as input parameters.
Titulo: Connected Three-Phase Boundary Length Evaluation in Modeled Sintered Composite Solid Oxide Fuel Cell Electrodes

Sentencas: Tomographic methods are used to reconstruct the modeled electrode and the percolation for each phase is evaluated.
Titulo: Connected Three-Phase Boundary Length Evaluation in Modeled Sintered Composite Solid Oxide Fuel Cell Electrodes

Sentencas: The connected TPBL is calculated for a range of electrode designs and comparisons are made with calculated TPBL values available in the literature.
Titulo: Connected Three-Phase Boundary Length Evaluation in Modeled Sintered Composite Solid Oxide Fuel Cell Electrodes

Sentencas: The maximum connected TPBL occurred at a porosity of 0.21 and at equal solid volume fractions of ionic and electronic conducting phases for particles having the same mean diameter and particle size variance.
Titulo: Connected Three-Phase Boundary Length Evaluation in Modeled Sintered Composite Solid Oxide Fuel Cell Electrodes

Sentencas: A cubic envelope having a minimum length of 14 times the mean particle diameter was necessary to adequately represent the electrode structure.
Titulo: Connected Three-Phase Boundary Length Evaluation in Modeled Sintered Composite Solid Oxide Fuel Cell Electrodes
